result.execSummary:
The defendant Julia Lynn Suter was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Julia Lynn Suter in court with attorney Paul Douglas Polacek.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Atty Hendee moves to amend Ct. 1 to Misd. Possession of THC.    Atty Hendee states plea agreement to the amended Ct. 1.  Atty Hendee has no objection to expungment after 12 months with conditions.  Atty Polacek agrees.  Defendant agrees.  
BY THE COURT:  Ct. 1 amended to Misd. Possession of THC 961.41 (3g)(e).

Defendant enters a No Contest plea.
  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.

  BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and finds defendant guilty of the amended Ct. 1.

Atty Polocek asks the court to follow the joint recommendation.

BY THE COURT:  Amended Ct. 1:  Pay fine and costs = $442.00
  DNA Sample + $200.00 Surcharge
  If after 12 months the defendant has paid the fine and costs in full and has had no criminal violations, the defendant may petition the court for Expungement 973.015.
  Defendant agrees to the $15.00 payment plan fee.
Payment Plan:  $50.00/month commencing in March

State files Information.  Atty Polacek receives the Information and waives it's reading.    Defendant stands mute.  Attorney request the Court enter a Not Guilty plea on behalf of the defendant.  BY THE COURT:  Court enters a Not Guilty plea on behalf of the defendant.  Bond continued.

Defendant Julia Lynn Suter in court with attorney Paul Douglas Polacek.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Defendant waives her right to preliminary hearing.  Court questions Atty Polacek.  Court questions defendant and accepts her waiver.  BY THE COURT:  Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and this defendant committed it.  Case bound over for trial or further proceedings.  Return date scheduled for December 16, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
